[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Understanding testing dependencies**\n\nI’m thinking about how test code can provide temporary working directories and directly instantiate components without Docker. There's a mention of JUnit in the generated scaffold, which might be included by TCK, but it seems that the existing build.gradle doesn’t add it. I'm considering whether Maven's test sources should use the maven-plugin-testing-harness, though it's not necessary for the generated tests. \n\nTo ensure meaningful coverage, I need to look into whether Gradle resolves runtime scope correctly and how dependencies are structured. It’s a bit tricky!\n\n**Clarifying dependency scopes**\n\nI'm analyzing runtime dependencies that appear on testRuntimeClasspath but not on testCompileClasspath. It seems that the native-image compile and run likely includes the runtime. For deterministic dependencies, it makes sense that the driver can only add testImplementation, not runtimeOnly. If tests require wagon-specific classes, testImplementation becomes necessary. But typically, generated tests shouldn’t import runtime provider classes unless they need to cover component loading. I'm realizing that the setup entries only list testImplementation dependencies. It's all a bit complex!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0dd18210c76a8fb9016a40a860b6108190bf2c09d0f27b35f3\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqQKhr3Ihc9yVAI_gN52KSzB68ZlkfHNi2GDXd2u94acmZWyGb8iE7EMp1PoYhzOaW0sbBKB4RP1je46w9ZTbrfZatUFtq0qQlymsNrfIFUn5Z2LdJ3z6H3yVhTfhZ2vOIr6cCnM3AWO165j0PTKrP2OP23gTmMHUBCAQDwbhMCKOOFY0LBiNLnRPZS6GxcdqMwIq_czUCEOF74xegxyQZ1XHNoQjj17lwReQo7i6YNkIlnOLZx4LklmT8onlJcV31j7U8NPDvYfUY1sEP6eU44yYMoPCi22iIwJDp_6MHkQ6eZiKHz6EqdQ7ZdH-WP-2LcWF8nLDB4hjH3rZqwt46Fkmd5d-SjHs_8LTRm-q3Ky_LNchFbEoexrOM6zT3FbE0-6M1x24vjohVPAlAWMtjtccLV7iA0OlZuvw0cphEZHPJ_W_Tx0525BImq8H6ndj2dyVJExqGmO2p5VBYqvLzkrhkt28ow1hBs8BCo